                <note rend="inline" type="source">818.6363/—: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hale</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San José</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-11-11T19:00:00-05:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 11, 1913, 7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received November 12, 8.50 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>In view of the situation it may be of interest to report that Richard Lloyd
                    George, son of the British Chancellor of the Exchequer, accompanies Robert
                    Anderson, who is seeking oil concession from Costa Rican Government for Pearson
                    and Son. Refer to Consul Lee’s unnumbered despatch November 4 entitled “Trade
                        Notes”.<note n="33" xml:id="d895fn33">Not found in Department files; for
                        text, see U.S. Department of Commerce, <hi rend="italic">Daily Consular and
                            Trade Reports</hi>, No. 274, Nov. 22, 1913, p. 991. It contains the
                        statement: “There is at present a proposition before Congress to grant a
                        concession to S. Pearson &amp; Son, of London, giving rights to explore and
                        develop possible oil fields in Costa Rica.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hale</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
